Black cherry trees I (17-50)

Analysis of wave velocity patterns in black cherry trees and its effect on internal decay detection https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0168169914000684

  • Sound wood. Tree 17, measured 50 cm above the ground.
  • The velocity is a quadratic function od the angle between the ray and the radial direction.

In[3]:
d = pd.DataFrame(index=df.columns, columns=df.columns)
d.iloc[1:,:] = df.values
for j in df.columns:
    d.loc[:,j] = np.roll(d.loc[:,j],j-1)
t2 = tomo.Tomo(speeds=d.values, nx=41, ny=41)
In[4]:
# Plot both original and fixed rays.
limits={"speed_min":np.nanmin(d.values), 
        "speed_max":np.nanmax(d.values)*1.12}
fig,ax = plt.subplots(2,2,figsize=(14,12))
t2.plot(grid=False, ax=ax[0,0], **limits)
t2.fix_velocity_EBSI()
t2.grid.set_cell_velocity_from_ray_means() # recalculate the means of velocities 

t2.plot(rays=False, ax=ax[1,0], shading='flat', **limits)
ax[1,0].axis('off')
ans = t2.do_EBSI_method(silent=False)
t2.plot(grid=False, ax=ax[0,1], **limits)
t2.plot(rays=False, ax=ax[1,1], **limits)
ax[0,0].set(title="Ray velocities")
ax[0,1].set(title="Compensated velocities")
ax[1,0].set(title="Basic method from mean values of rays (velocities compensated)")
ax[1,1].set(title="EBSI method")
plt.suptitle("Original ray speeds, compensated ray speeds, cell speeds from means of"+
             " rays through the cell and cell speeds from EBSI method.", wrap=True)
plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.03, 1, 0.95]) # see https://stackoverflow.com/questions/8248467/tight-layout-doesnt-take-into-account-figure-suptitle
